SIMPLE: part
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Part
<hw>Part</hw> <pr>(p⟦aum⟧rt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>part</ets>, L. <ets>pars</ets>, gen. <ets>partis</ets>; cf.
<ets>parere</ets> to bring forth, produce. Cf. <er>Parent</er>,
<er>Depart</er>, <er>Parcel</er>, <er>Partner</er>, <er>Party</er>,
<er>Portion</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of the portions, equal or
unequal, into which anything is divided, or regarded as divided;
something less than a <contr>whole</contr>; a number, quantity, mass, or
the like, regarded as going to make up, with others, a larger number,
quantity, mass, etc., whether actually separate or not; a piece; a
fragment; a fraction; a division; a member; a constituent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And kept back <qex>part</qex> of the price, . . . and brought a
certain <qex>part</qex> and laid it at the apostles'feet.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts v. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our ideas of extension and number -- do they not contain a secret
relation of the <qex>parts</qex> ?</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am a <qex>part</qex> of all that I have met.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence, specifically:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>An equal constituent portion; one of several or many like
quantities, numbers, etc., into which anything is divided, or of which
it is composed; proportional division or ingredient.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An homer is the tenth <qex>part</qex> of an ephah.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. xvi. 36.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A thought which, quartered, hath but one <qex>part</qex>
wisdom,⟦br⟧
And ever three <qex>parts</qex> coward.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A constituent portion of a living or spiritual
whole; a member; an organ; an essential element.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the <qex>parts</qex> were formed . . . into one harmonious
body.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pulse, the glow of every <qex>part</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>A constituent of character or capacity; quality;
faculty; talent; -- usually in the plural with a collective sense.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Men of considerable <xex>parts</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Burke.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧Great quickness of <xex>parts</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Macaulay.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which maintained so politic a state of evil, that they will not
admit any good <qex>part</qex> to intermingle with them.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>Quarter; region; district; -- usually in the
plural.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The uttermost <xex>part</xex> of the heaven.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Neh. i. 9.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All <qex>parts</qex> resound with tumults, plaints, and fears.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Such portion of any quantity, as
when taken a certain number of times, will exactly make that quantity;
<as>as, 3 is a <ex>part</ex> of 12;</as> -- the opposite of
<contr>multiple</contr>. Also, a line or other element of a geometrical
figure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which belongs to one, or which is assumed by
one, or which falls to one, in a division or apportionment; share;
portion; lot; interest; concern; duty; office.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have no <qex>part</qex> in David.</q> <rj><qau>2 Sam. xx.
1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Accuse not Nature! she hath done her <qex>part</qex>;⟦br⟧
Do thou but thine.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let me bear⟦br⟧
My <qex>part</qex> of danger with an equal share.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Hence, specifically:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>One of the opposing parties or sides in a conflict or a
controversy; a faction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For he that is not against us is on our <qex>part</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Mark ix. 40.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Make whole kingdoms take her brother's <qex>part</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A particular character in a drama or a play; an
assumed personification; also, the language, actions, and influence of a
character or an actor in a play; or, figuratively, in real life; <as>as,
to play the <ex>part</ex> of Macbeth</as>. See <cref>To act a
part</cref>, under <er>Act</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That <qex>part</qex>⟦br⟧
Was aptly fitted and naturally performed.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was a brute <qex>part</qex> of him to kill so capital a
calf.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Honor and shame from no condition rise;⟦br⟧
Act well your <qex>part</qex>, there all the honor lies.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>One of the different melodies of
a concerted composition, which heard in union compose its harmony; also,
the music for each voice or instrument; <as>as, the treble, tenor, or
bass <ex>part</ex>; the violin <ex>part</ex>, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>For my part</b></col>, <cd>so far as concerns me; for my
share.</cd> -- <col><b>For the most part</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Most</er>, <pos>a.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>In good part</b></col>,
<cd>as well done; favorably; acceptably; in a friendly manner; <as>as,
to take an act <ex>in good part</ex></as>.</cd> <au>Hooker.</au> --
<col><b>In ill part</b></col>, <cd>unfavorably; with displeasure.</cd>
-- <col><b>In part</b></col>, <cd>in some degree; partly.</cd> --
<col><b>Part and parcel</b></col>, <cd>an essential or constituent
portion; -- a reduplicative phrase. Cf. <cref>might and main</cref>,
<cref>kith and kin</cref>, etc.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧She was . . . <xex>part and
parcel</xex> of the race and place.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Howitt.</au> --
<col><b>Part of speech</b></col> <fld>(Gram.)</fld>, <cd>a sort or class
of words of a particular character; <as>thus, the noun is a <ex>part of
speech</ex> denoting the name of a thing; the verb is a <ex>part of
speech</ex> which asserts something of the subject of a
sentence</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Part owner</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>,
<cd>one of several owners or tenants in common. See <cref>Joint
tenant</cref>, under <er>Joint</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Part
singing</b></col>, <cd>singing in which two or more of the harmonic
parts are taken.</cd> -- <col><b>Part song</b></col>, <cd>a song in two
or more (commonly four) distinct vocal parts.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>part
song</xex> differs from a madrigal in its exclusion of contrapuntual
devices; from a glee, in its being sung by many voices, instead of by
one only, to each part.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Stainer & Barrett.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Portion; section; division; fraction; fragment;
piece; share; constituent. See <er>Portion</er>, and
<er>Section</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Part</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Part
<hw>Part</hw> <pr>(p⟦aum⟧rt)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Parted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Parting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>partir</ets>, L.
<ets>partire</ets>, <ets>partiri</ets>, p. p. <ets>partitus</ets>, fr.
<ets>pars</ets>, gen. <ets>partis</ets>, a part. See <er>Part</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To divide; to separate into distinct parts; to break
into two or more parts or pieces; to sever.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Thou shalt
<xex>part</xex> it in pieces.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Lev. ii. 6.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There, [celestial love] <qex>parted</qex> into rainbow hues.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To divide into shares; to divide and distribute; to
allot; to apportion; to share.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>part</qex> his throne, and share his heaven with thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>parted</qex> my raiment among them.</q> <rj><qau>John
xix. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To separate or disunite; to cause to go apart; to
remove from contact or contiguity; to sunder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord do so to me, and more also, if aught but death
<qex>part</qex> thee and me.</q> <rj><qau>Ruth i. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While he blessed them, he was <qex>parted</qex> from them, and
carried up into heaven.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xxiv. 51.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The narrow seas that <qex>part</qex>⟦br⟧
The French and English.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To hold apart; to stand
between; to intervene betwixt, as combatants.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The stumbling night did <qex>part</qex> our weary powers.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To separate by a process of extraction, elimination,
or secretion; <as>as, to <ex>part</ex> gold from silver</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The liver minds his own affair, . . .⟦br⟧
And <qex>parts</qex> and strains the vital juices.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To leave; to quit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Since presently your souls must <qex>part</qex> your bodies.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To separate (a collection of objects) into smaller
collections; <as>as, to <ex>part</ex> one's hair in the
middle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To part a cable</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
break it.</cd> -- <col><b>To part company</b></col>, <cd>to separate, as
travelers or companions.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Part</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Part
<hw>Part</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be broken or divided
into parts or pieces; to break; to become separated; to go asunder;
<as>as, rope <ex>parts</ex>; his hair <ex>parts</ex> in the
middle.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To go away; to depart; to take leave; to quit each
other; hence, to die; -- often with <xex>from</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He wrung Bassanio's hand, and so they <qex>parted</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He owned that he had <qex>parted</qex> from the duke only a few
hours before.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His precious bag, which he would by no means <qex>part</qex>
from.</q> <rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To perform an act of parting; to relinquish a
connection of any kind; -- followed by <ptcl>with</ptcl> or
<ptcl>from</ptcl>; <as>as, to <ex>part</ex> with one's
money</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Celia, for thy sake, I <qex>part</qex>⟦br⟧
With all that grew so near my heart.</q> <rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Powerful hands . . . will not <qex>part</qex>⟦br⟧
Easily from possession won with arms.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was strange to him that a father should feel no tenderness at
<qex>parting</qex> with an only son.</q> <rj><qau>A.
Trollope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To have a part or share; to partake.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧They shall <xex>part</xex> alike.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>1 Sam. xxx. 24.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Part</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Part
<hw>Part</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Partly; in a measure.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Partable</ent>⟦br⟧
